Subject: Destroyers (Warships)

Rights.rightsHolderContact: The Regents of the University of California
Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Department of Special Collections
Rights.servicesContact: UCLA Library Special Collections, A1713 Charles E. Young Research Library, Box 951575, Los Angeles, CA 90095-1575. Email: spec-coll@library.ucla.edu. Phone: (310) 825-4953
Relation.isPartOf: Los Angeles Times Photographic Archive. Department of Special Collections, Charles E. Young Research Library, UCLA.
Title: HMCS Vancouver (D05 / F6A / H55) destroyer, Los Angeles, 1936
Description.caption: Text from negative sleeve: Canada, Navy, Ships, Destroyers|~|Handwritten on negative: Vancouver
Description.note: Reported in “Canadian ships visit: Skeena and Vancouver of Pacific Detail open to public today,” Los Angeles Times, 19 Apr. 1936: A2.|~|The first s hip named HMCS Vancouver, initially named HMS Toreador, this ship was originally commissioned in the Royal Navy in 1919. She was loaned to the Royal Canadian Navy that was awaiting the completion of new ships ordered to replenish its aging fleet. Her transfer took place at Portsmouth, England, on March 1, 1928, and the ship was re-named Vancouver in honour of the explorer. In May 1928, Vancouver arrived at Esquimalt, British Columbia, and was utilized to provide reserve training on the west coast. She was paid off on November 25, 1936, and sold for scrap the following year.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.|~|Access to this collection is generously supported by Haynes Foundation funds.

Title: John Moore watches William Focher die after being shot by police, Los Angeles, 1935
Description.caption: Text from negative sleeve: 1147-- John G. Moore, William Focher-- Focher dying, Shooting of Focher, 9/11/35|~|Handwritten on negative: William Focher, John G. Moore
Description.note: Shortly after an altercation with wrestling promoter Lou Daro 35-year-old William Focher was shot by police officers after they had confused him for a bandit. After several hours of being treated at the hospital he died.|~|Similar photograph appears with the article, "Error Death to be Aired," Los Angeles Times, 12 July 1935: A1.|~|A few men can be seen standing around William as he looks up from a bed with his mouth open, a blood pressure cuff rapped around one tattooed arm. The time the picture was taken is not given, but it is assumed to be sometime between Focher's admission to the hospital and his death. His friend, John G. Moore turns his face to look at him. A female's arm/hand can be seen touching the bed as well. One man smokes while watching while another with a hat watches in front of Focher.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.|~|Access to this collection is generously supported by Haynes Foundation funds.|~|Access to this collection is generously supported by Haynes Foundation funds.

Title: Alice Pheland and B. F. Enyeart pose in front of the Burbank City Schools' Tournament of Roses parade float framework, Pasadena vicinity, about 1936
Description.caption: Handwritten on negative: L to R. Alice Phelan B. J. Enyear [sic]|~|Handwritten text from negative sleeve: 3183 - L to R. Alice Phelan Art supervisor and B. F. Enyeart, Supt of Burbank schools. supervise Rose float for Burbank. 1-10-36 [date stamp:] 1936
Description.note: A different photograph of the same Burbank parade float appears with the title, "Somebody Stole Burbank Rose Float Money--but Job Goes On!," and is captioned, "Theft of funds intended for Burbank School's entry in the Rose Tournament Parade at Pasadena, from a school safe Monday night, will not prevent construction of the Burbank entry, it was announced yesterday. The loss totaled $100. Some of the fund already had been spent and part of it was kept elsewhere. School officials, however, will replace the loss. The theme of the float will be "Chivalry." Jackie Searl, juvenile actor, who attends Burbank High School, will ride his own horse ahead of the float. Shown above, working on entry, is B. F. Enyeart, superintendent of schools, at extreme left., and school board members who volunteered to lend a hand to rush construction of the colorful creation. Times photo," Los Angeles Times, 27 Dec. 1935: 6|~|Text from accompanying note card in negative sleeve (Item Ark: 21198/zz002h823d ): ENYEARST [sic]. BUEL F. SEPT 16 34 BURBANK: SCHOOLS: SUPT. High school principal is named by Bd. of Educ. to fill position vacated by Curtis E. Warren, supt. of schools. (Burbank) 1-20-1|~|At center, from left to right, Alice Phelan and B. F. Enyeart, Burbank Schools Superintendent, pose in front of the framework for the Burbank City Schools' float entry into the Tournament of Roses. They both stand in profile, facing left, but turn their heads towards camera. Alice Phelan holds onto the framework behind her as she casts her gaze downward. The incomplete float stands in partial view behind them. Its design appears to emulate tracery and stained glass elements seen in Gothic architecture.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.|~|Access to this collection is generously supported by Haynes Foundation funds.

Description.caption: Handwritten text from negative sleeve: 3321 - Army plane crash at Monterey Park. Plane crash cra[?]e: de[?]lict back one a[?]ter. 4-4-36 [date stamp:] APR 14 1936
Description.note: A grain field in Monterey Park stretches across the foreground and back through the image. In the near distance at center, the wreckage of Lieutenant Browne Clement's aircraft lies crumpled on the ground. Along part of the plane, it reads, "52." The tail of the plane sits hidden behind a group of several investigators, who stand in a cluster to the right of the aircraft. Beyond the wreckage site, the field extends into the distance and towards 2 low mountains that rise at far left and far right.|~|This photograph is related to the article, "Death Ends Honeymoon: CRASH KILLS ARMY FLYER Plane Propeller Comes Off, Wrecking Wing, and Ship Goes Into Spin," Los Angeles Times, 05 Apr. 1936: 1|~|A different photograph of the same plane crash appears with the caption, "Propeller Comes Off, Wrecking Airplane Wreckage of Lieut. Title: Military personnel scour through the wreckage of Lieutenant Browne Clement's downed aircraft, Monterey Park, 1936
Description.caption: Handwritten text from negative sleeve: 3321 - Army plane crash at Monterey Park. Plane crash cra[?]e: de[?]lict back one a[?]ter. 4-4-36 [date stamp:] APR 14 1936
Description.note: This photograph is related to the article, "Death Ends Honeymoon: CRASH KILLS ARMY FLYER Plane Propeller Comes Off, Wrecking Wing, and Ship Goes Into Spin," Los Angeles Times, 05 Apr. 1936: 1|~|A different photograph of the same plane crash appears with the caption, "Propeller Comes Off, Wrecking Airplane Wreckage of Lieut. Browne Clement's' army pursuit plane in grain field at Monterey Park with March Field mechanics disassembling it for return to airport. Propeller shown in foreground was retrieved from front yard 500 yards away. Times photo," Los Angeles Times, 05 Apr. 1936: 2|~|In the near distance at center, several members of the armed forces scour through the wreckage of Lieutenant Browne Clement's downed aircraft. The wreckage lies crumpled in a grain field and is viewed from the side. An identification mark on the tail of the plane at left reads, "52." Three men stand on the near side of the plane with their backs to the camera. Some debris from the crash lies between the camera and the nearest man. The outer layer of the plane is gone, allowing the camera a glimpse into the inner structure of plane's side. A few more men stand behind and to the left of the plane. The grain field stretches into the distance.

Title: Sheriff Eugene Biscailuz and Bill Jenkins sit atop bicycles and pose with fellow Wheelmen during a meeting, Los Angeles vicinity, 1938
Description.caption: Handwritten text from negative sleeve: 14978 - wheelsmen + Sheriff Biscailuz 11-15-38 [date stamp:] NOV 23 1938 [credit stamp:] TIMES PHOTO BY ANDREW H. ARNOTT|~|Handwritten on negative: wheelmen 11-14-38 7 x [?...]
Description.note: A similar photograph of the same Wheelsmen’s organization meeting appears in a photospread titled, “Italy Pours 20,000 Emigrants From 15 Liners Into African Colony, Libya,” and captioned, “Old-Time Cyclists To Hold Annual Dinner Meet Bill Jenkins, left, Tracy Q. Hall and Sheriff Gene Biscailuz, members of Wheelmen’s organization, stand beside one of the vehicles which they rode over Southland roads in past century, as they talk over the plans for the annual dinner to be held Saturday night. Times photo,” Los Angeles Times, 15 Nov. 1938: 22|~|This photographis related to the article, “Wheelmen Plan Dinner: Annual Fete to Be Held Saturday,” Los Angeles Times, 15 Nov. 1938: A2|~|Several members of the club, Wheelmen of the Past Century, don suits and pose, off-center to the right, in a parking lot. Two among the group sit atop bicycles. Sheriff Eugene Biscailuz sits front and center atop a bicycle. He and the bicycle are viewed from the side, facing right. He turns his head to smile to the camera. An unidentified man kneels on the ground to the right of Sheriff Biscailuz's front tire and points up towards Sheriff Biscailuz. Behind and to the right of Sheriff Biscailuz, Bill Jenkins sits on a high-wheeler. He and the bicycle face towards the left. He too turns his head towards the camera. Six more men stand around the bicycles and either look to the camera or look towards Bill Jenkins. Beyond the parking lot the group stands in, a cliff wall stretches across the background. A building, in partial view, rises along the left edge.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.|~|Access to this collection is generously supported by Haynes Foundation funds.

Title: Correspondence from Albert F. Coyle to Governor Friend W. Richardson, 1926
Description.caption: Text from negative sleeve: Richardson, Friend (Gov of CA.) X Box 28
Description.note: Photograph of a typescript letter from Albert F. Coyle, Acting Editor and Publicity Manager for the Brotherhood of Locomotive Engineers Journal to Friend W. Richardson, Governor of California. The letter is dated December 15, 1926. Albert F. Coyle writes to request a Christmas-time pardon for James B. McNamara from San Quentin prison. McNamara and others were responsible for the Los Angeles Times bombing in 1910.

Title: June Robles with unidentified children and a young woman, on a visit to see her relatives in Glendale, California, 1934
Description.caption: Text from newspaper caption for similar photograph: June Robles Frolicking With Father June Robles, Arizona kidnap victim, proved, when she arrived in Glendale yesterday to visit her grandmother and other relatives, that despite her harrowing desert experience she still enjoys riding piggy-back on the shoulders of her father, Ferdinand Robles.|~|A similar photograph with June Robles wearing the same dress appears with the article, "Robles Girl Visits Here," Los Angeles Times, 26 May 1934: A1.|~|Text from negative sleeve: Robles, June. Her father, Fernando, also claims that June is doing very well since her rescue from the shallow pit she had been imprisoned in in the desert, having gained eight pounds. All questions June was asked concerning the kidnapping were answered with "I don't know."

Description.note: From left to right, Judge Charles Fricke and Deputy District Attorney George Stahlman handle evidence in the courtroom during the Nellie Madison trial. Judge Fricke stands nearer to camera and faces towards the right. He looks down at a revolver he holds in his hands. Evidence tags hang from the revolver. To the right of him, the victim's bed enters frame. Behind the headboard, Deputy D. A. George Stahlman stands. He leans over and looks towards the Judge while pointing to a hole in a blanket. The Judge's bench sits at left and the chamber's door sits ajar at right.|~|This photograph is either related to the article, "MADISON JURORS SEE DEATH BED: Defense Loses Battle to Prevent Introduction Bullet Holes in Sheet Cited as Proof of Shooting Officers Testify at Trial of Widow in Murder Case," Los Angeles Times, 12 Jun. 1934: A2 or the article, "MADISON MAY BE EXHUMED: Defense Asserts Willingness Ex-Wife of Supposed Victim Says Slain Man Was Her Former Mate Accused Window Denies She Hid as Officers Neared Scene of Arrest," Los Angeles Times, 16 Jun. 1934: A1|~|This photograph is similar to another taken during the Nellie Madison trial captioned, "Accused Widow Rearranges Deathbed in Court," Los Angeles Times, 16 Jun. 1934: 14

Off-center to the right, the stone porch and chimneys of the Steeles' fire-destroyed home are all that remain of the ranch house. The large porch is constructed entirely of stone. Behind and to the left of the house's remains, several men are visible combing through the rest of the rubble and debris. An outbuilding stands along the left edge, behind the debris. Silhouetted mountains rise across the background.|~|This photograph is related to the article, "SEEK CLEWS TO DOUBLE MURDER IN HOME RUIN.: Friends of Dead Rich Man and Wife Suspect Slaying by Incendiary; Accident, Officers Believe. Title: Actor Del Lawrence in an American Indian costume at the Mason Theatre in downtown Los Angeles, 1936
Description.caption: Text from negative sleeve: Del Stone Lawrence... (P.W.A [sic] Theatre - Mason Theatre). 4/21/36|~|Handwritten on negative: Del Stone Lawrence.
Description.note: Related to: “Boucicault's 'Octoroon' Revived at Mason Theater,” Los Angeles Times , 22 Apr. 1936: 9.|~|Stage and screen actor Del Lawrence (also known as Del Stone Lawrence, and Landen Stone Gans) is viewed from the back seated at a desk and reflected in a mirror. He is wearing a costume of an American Indian feather headdress. Lawrence was playing the character of "Wahnotee" (an "Indian Chief") in a revival of Dion Boucicault's The Octoroon. It is likely that this photograph was taken at the Mason Theatre in downtown Los Angeles, as part of the Works Progress Administration (WPA) Federal Theatre Project.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.|~|Access to this collection is generously supported by Haynes Foundation funds.

Title: Arthur B. Dodge, art director of the Los Angeles Times, 1936
Description.caption: Text from negative sleeve: Mr. “Boss Dodge” 5275. Date stamp: May 17 [1936]
Description.note: Arthur Burnside Dodge was born in Providence, Rhode Island, ban his family moved to California in 1864. For ten they lived in Grass Valley, then settled in San Francisco. There he began his career as a wood engraver at age 18 and spent five years in New York City studying art. Upon returning to San Francisco, he was an illustrator for local newspapers from 1890 until 1901. He then moved to Los Angeles where he continued newspaper work. After four years at the Morning Herald, he spent 42 years as art director at the Los Angeles Times. Known as "Boss" to his friends, he died in Los Angeles in 1952.|~|“A. B. (Boss) Dodge, noted artist, dies,” Los Angeles Times, 12 Jun. 1952: A1.|~|Portrait photograph of Arthur "Boss" Dodge.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.|~|Access to this collection is generously supported by Haynes Foundation funds.

She was predeceased by her husbands, Valentine Everit Macy, Jr., Ranieri Bourbon Del Monte Santa Maria, Prince di San Faustino (Italy) and Roland Livingston Redmond.
